{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"53fa1412-da6e-4193-b1f0-92ace413bf44","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_kvCbS8nGn9IXCBJbAfNGw1","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-81e1fbd2b58d432c8daec44325e0ec43"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-81e1fbd2b58d432c8daec44325e0ec43."}],"interactionId":"b73fdafe-4da0-4806-9630-a5ff5276be0d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but strongly recommended for validation and editor support. The standard value is `http://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packages, especially if you plan to have multiple related templates. Not strictly required though.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of a template exist. Not strictly required.\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Optional but good practice.\n\n\n5. **`defaultValue` references `net9.0`** — This is fine if targeting .NET 9.\n6. **Missing `description`** — Not strictly required by the engine, but highly recommended for NuGet gallery discoverability.\n\nNow I'm distinguishing between what the template engine actually requires versus what's just good practice. The core mandatory fields are `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, and `classifications`, which you already have covered.\n\nThe real issue is that `description` is missing—while the engine doesn't enforce it, the NuGet gallery definitely needs it for users to understand what the template does. I should also check whether you have a `.nuspec` or `.csproj` file set up for packaging, since the `template.json` alone won't get this published to NuGet.","outputTokens":565,"requestId":"481E:38B4C:1437DD:182170:69EABF51"},"id":"e4223089-cac7-41e2-b562-0c69ec7418e3","timestamp":"2